To get rid of the NA’s we use a measure of center (median) and impute. In both instances we take the mean of the ABV and IBU for each style of beverage, then replace the NA value in the ABV column based on the Style of beverage it is. This takes care of the 62 NA’s for “ABV” column. We do the same for the IBU column. Lastly, to address the NA’s under “Style” we took the mode (another measure of center) and replaced the five NA’s with the most popular Style.

8. Budweiser would also like to investigate the difference with respect to IBU

and ABV between IPAs (India Pale Ales) and other types of Ale (any beer with “Ale” in its name other than IPA).

You decide to use KNN classification to investigate this relationship. Provide statistical evidence one way or the other.

You can of course assume your audience is comfortable with percentages

# Filter dataset for IPAs and Ales
beers_breweries_knn <-
  beers_breweries |> 
    mutate(Classification = as.factor(ifelse( grepl("India Pale Ale|IPA",Style, ignore.case = TRUE) == 1, "IPA",
                                              ifelse(grepl("Ale",Style, ignore.case = FALSE) == 1, "Other", "")))) |> 
  filter(Classification != "") |> 
  droplevels(beers_breweries$Classification)

dim(beers_breweries_knn) #1538 rows
## [1] 1538   16
# partitioning the data
trainInd = sample(seq(1,1538,1), 1538*.7) # creating random sample indexes
training = beers_breweries_knn[trainInd,] # train data
testing = beers_breweries_knn[-trainInd,] # test data

# using knn to classify style of beer using ABV and IBU in the new testing set
classifications = knn(training[,c(2,3)], testing[,c(2,3)], training$Classification, k = 15, prob = TRUE)
# creating confusion matrix to calculate the accuracy, misclassification rate,
# sensitivity and specificity
confusionMatrix(classifications, testing$Classification )
## Confusion Matrix and Statistics
## 
##           Reference
## Prediction IPA Other

accuracy <- sum(classifications == testing$Classification) / length(testing$Classification)
paste("Accuracy:", round(accuracy * 100, 2), "%")
## [1] "Accuracy: 88.31 %"
  • Accuracy: Approximately 90% percent of the prediction were correct.
  • Sensitivity: About 80% of the actual IPAs were correctly identified. This means that out of all the IPAs, our model was able to identify 80% correctly. -Specificity: Approximately 94% of the time, our model correctly identified ‘Other’ beers. This tells us that it’s quite good at identifying beers that are not IPAs


# Using statistical tests to see if the differences in IBU and ABV between IPAs and other 
# Ales are statistically significant

# T-test for ABV
t_test_abv <- t.test(ABV ~ Classification, data = beers_breweries_knn)

# T-test for IBU
t_test_ibu <- t.test(IBU ~ Classification, data = beers_breweries_knn)

# Output the t-test results
list(ABV_T_Test = t_test_abv, IBU_T_Test = t_test_ibu)

ABV

The t-test results show that there is a statistically significant difference in ABV between IPAs and Pale Ales, with IPAs having a higher mean ABV. The extremely low p-value suggests that the observed difference is very unlikely to be due to chance. This could indicate that IPAs are generally stronger in terms of alcohol content compared to Pale Ales, which might reflect consumer preferences for stronger beers in the segment of the market that prefers IPAs. This insight can be valuable for Budweiser in tailoring their product offerings to meet consumer preferences or in targeting marketing efforts for different beer styles

IBU

The t-test indicates a significant difference in bitterness between IPAs and Pale Ales, with IPAs being much more bitter on average. This finding is highly statistically significant and suggests that when it comes to bitterness, these two styles of beer cater to distinct taste preferences. For Budweiser, this might imply a focus on marketing IPAs to consumers who prefer a bitter taste and Pale Ales to those who prefer a less bitter beer. It can also inform decisions on product development and positioning within the market

#Exploring the distribution of ABV and IBU across different beer styles


# ABV distribution across top 10 beer styles
# Filter for only the top 10 most common beer styles
top_styles <- beers_breweries |>
  count(Style) |>
  top_n(10, n) |>
  pull(Style)

filtered_data <- beers_breweries |>
  filter(Style %in% top_styles)
library(ggplot2)
# Creating the boxplot with the filtered data
ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = reorder(Style, ABV, FUN = median), y = ABV)) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(color = Style)) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
        legend.position = "none") +
  labs(title = "ABV Distribution Across Top 10 Beer Styles", x = "Beer Style", y = "ABV") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))  # Center the plot title

A quick glance at the plot suggests that there is considerable diversity in ABV across beer styles. Some styles, like American Double/Imperial IPA, have a higher median ABV, reflecting their stronger profiles. The range of ABV values within styles could reflect diverse consumer preferences, with some consumers preferring lighter beers and others seeking stronger options.

# IBU distribution across beer styles
ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = reorder(Style, IBU, FUN = median), y = IBU)) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(color = Style)) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        legend.position = "none") + 
  labs(title = "IBU Distribution Across Top 10 Beer Styles", x = "Beer Style", y = "IBU")

Beer styles with higher IBU are often perceived as more bitter, and this plot shows which styles tend to have higher bitterness levels. This information could help Budweiser decide on product development strategies, such as creating beers that fit popular or niche bitterness profiles. Understanding the range and common values of IBU for popular styles can also inform quality control and consistency efforts in beer production.
